div.p:
MNES. On this account then Philocles,6 as he is ugly, com­ 

            poses uglily; and Xenocles,7 as he is vile, composes vilely; 

            and Theognis,8 again, as he is frigid, composes frigidly.

BAC. Aye, by Ceres, with a tunic of fine wool underneath; 

            and if he impose upon them by saying this, he emerges again 

            in the fish-market.7

EUR. You have made a still greater blunder than I wanted ; 

            for if he have obtained the Terrestrial prerogative from his 

            father—

ÆSCH. One must not rear a lion's whelp1 within the city; 

            above all not rear a lion in the city; but if one rear it, one 

            must submit to its ways.

BLEP. Now about making innovations,2 don't be alarmed; 

            for to do this and to neglect what is ancient, is with us equi­ 

            valent to another constitution.

CHR. You shall hear: for the god told me this plainly; 

            whomsoever I should first meet with3 on going out,4 him he bid 

            me5 never let go, but prevail on him to accompany me home.

CA. Not yet. And after this now I did a very laughable 

            thing indeed ; for as he was approaching, I farted very loudly ; 

            for my belly6 had been blown out.
